<html>
<body>
Reports any references to classes from the default package in JSP files.

<p><b>Example:</b></p>
<pre><code lang="jsp">
  &lt;%!
  Integer countSomeUsefulStuff() {
    ...
    new ClassFromDefaultPackage(...); // Error
    new com.example.GoodClass(...); // Good
  }
  %&gt;
  &lt;html&gt;
    &lt;head&gt;
      &lt;title&gt;Hello, JSP!&lt;/title&gt;
    &lt;/head&gt;
  &lt;/html&gt;
</code></pre><br/>
<!-- tooltip end -->
<p>
  <b>NOTE:</b> Such references will not be resolved during compilation of the JSP
  because a compiled class for the JSP will be usually placed in non-default package
  (for example, "org.apache.jsp" in case of Tomcat, "com.ibm._jsp" in case of WebSphere),
  but importing from the default package is not allowed in Java.
</p>
</body>
</html>
